Giant info dump on the BSOIC problems today & the solution we implemented
text: There's an LCLS-II BSOIC PLC in rack 5 in the sector 29 I&C alcove that has inputs from various LCLS-II BSOICs (none of which are required by any active BAS). This PLC is already tied into the ABC BSOICs PLC in B005, which in turn sends an "All BSOICs Okay" signal to the East Global state machine. The LCLS-II BSOIC PLC in S29 was sending out a faulted signal. I got Eric Tse on Facetime and we examined it together. At first it appeared that two of the BSOIC inputs to that PLC were faulted. However, we examined those BSOICs locally and both looked perfectly happy. We tried resetting the BSOIC PLC several times. Each time it would come up okay, then fault again shortly thereafter. We concluded that the problem is with one of the cables, or within the PLC itself, or perhaps in one of the relays. Not something that could be fixed on short notice. Therefore, we decided to bypass this PLC's input to the ABC BSOICs PLC in B005. That bypass is covered under RSWCF 8613. I've attached a bunch of pictures to this entry; here's what each picture shows. Fig. 1: S29 BSOICs interface panel viewed from the front of the racks (had to unscrew + remove a face plate to access this panel). Fig. 2: S29 BSOICs interface panel closeup view. The reset button we used is on the bottom right side. Fig. 3: S29 BSOICs PLC in the faulted state (as found upon opening the rack). This PLC is accessed from the rear of rack 5. Fig. 4: S29 BSOICs PLC in the reset state. Faulted again shortly thereafter. Fig. 5: The rack in B005 that contains the ABC BSOICs PLC. Rack 25 is the second from the left as you face west (upstream relative to the beamline). Fig. 6: ABC BSOICs PLC. The bypass cable that I installed is visible at the right (large red cable). Fig. 7: Closeup view of the installed bypass cable. This bypass allowed us to clear the fault and restore beam.

title: Shantha figured out some really weird stuff about TCAV0
text: At first there was confusion in that she could get more response by turning up the clipping limits on the PAC out AMPL. Later recognized that this might be simply due to very low SBST output. Looking at diagnostic PAD, the waveforms looked pretty flat, but occasionally we saw what looked like a mistimed BV pulse. Moving the trigger to the diagnostic PAD from +3820ns to -1830nS would "occassionally" give us a set of waveforms seen below. PAC out looks plenty healthy. KLYS drive looks pretty weak. KLYS FWD also looks pretty weak. These waveforms only look like this for a very short period of time, then most of the time there are flatlined. This must have something to do with standby/accelerate (we are trying to look at this at accelerate). Conclude something is probably wrong with the SBST at least...and potentially the overall trigger setup.

title: * Re: Schlotter working on gas attenuation and enabling the PIMPs associated.
text: Bill was unable to set the attenuation between the GMD and XGMD, and we decided that troubleshooting this does not need to happen tonight. The slits are in and should protect downstream components but the ~4 mJ we have now is probably as high as we should go (which should be more than enough for the program that will use it). When we establish the 700 eV SXR beam later the attenuation should work better, but the transmission is currently set to 1.0 (max transmission) and we will not be able to change that from the ACR. Since the slits are in, downstream components will still be protected as long as we do not get too much pulse intensity so we should not tune the SCR beam more than we need to. In summary, please do not tune the SXR beam higher than 3-4 mJ tonight.

title: * Re: Shantha worked on the XTCAV for several hours today but it's not functional yet
text: XTCAV Trigger system unstable. Tried the following steps and the trigger jumps were noticed in all tests after a while. 1. Directly connected the MKSUII Trigger Output from its front panel to PAD3 (CH3 monitors X-Band Phase Reference). 2. XTCAV PAC STBY Trigger input comes from the MKSUII rear panel. T-ed off PAC STBY Trigger input with PAD3 trigger input. 3. Add delay lines to the input of triggers at both send and receive end of the PAD3 trigger. 4. Replace the B921 Timing distribution Fanout fiber with the Undulator EVR fanout fiber from the tunner. 5. Adjust low level EVR-DMPH-RF02 by a tick or two for TTB2 (HXR STBY trigger). The EVR output triggers go to two small PULSE devices. Some random clicking noises were heard from possibly internal relays of one of the trigger fanout PULSE devices. May be this little piece of electronics is the source of the trigger issues?
